      <h2 class="font-crimson text-[30px] md:text-[40px] text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6">Pro Tips from Years of Experience</h2>
      
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-50 to-indigo-50 border-2 border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6">
          <h3 class="font-crimson text-lg font-medium text-blue-900 mb-3">✨ Always Keep a Master File</h3>
          <p class="text-blue-800 text-sm">
            Save your original design at the highest possible resolution (even 6000x6000) in a lossless format like PSD or TIFF. Export 3000x3000 versions as needed. This gives you flexibility for future uses.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-50 to-indigo-50 border-2 border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6">
          <h3 class="font-crimson text-lg font-medium text-blue-900 mb-3">🎨 Design for the Square</h3>
          <p class="text-blue-800 text-sm">
            Don't just crop a landscape photo into a square—compose your image knowing it will be square. Center important elements and avoid placing crucial details near edges.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-50 to-indigo-50 border-2 border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6">
          <h3 class="font-crimson text-lg font-medium text-blue-900 mb-3">💾 Name Files Descriptively</h3>
          <p class="text-blue-800 text-sm">
            Use clear names like "AlbumTitle_3000x3000_RGB.jpg" instead of "IMG_1234.jpg". When you're managing multiple projects, this saves enormous time and prevents mistakes.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-50 to-indigo-50 border-2 border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6">
          <h3 class="font-crimson text-lg font-medium text-blue-900 mb-3">🔍 Test Before Submission</h3>
          <p class="text-blue-800 text-sm">
            View your 3000x3000 image at actual size (100% zoom) to check for artifacts, blur, or compression issues. What looks good at thumbnail size may have problems at full resolution.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

